         b'a></div>\n\t\t\t<div class="alignright"><a href="http://mobblog.cs.u'
         b'cl.ac.uk/2007/09/09/barcamp-for-mobile-interaction-designers-and-dev'
         b'elopers/" rel="next">Barcamp for mobile designers and developers &ra'
         b'quo;</a></div>\n\t\t</div>\n\n\t\t<div class="post-74 post type-pos'
         b't status-publish format-standard hentry category-conference category'
         b'-research" id="post-74">\n\t\t\t<h2>Roundup of Papers in Mobiquitous'
         b'</h2>\n\n\t\t\t<div class="entry">\n\t\t\t\t<p>Here are some  pape'
         b'rs presented at Mobiquitous. I&#8217;ll introduce them by  research '
         b'areas.</p>\n<p><span id="more-74"></span></p>\n<p><strong>Object T'
         b'racking</strong><br />\nTo track mobile objects (e.g., mobile pho'
         b'nes, books, children), one may require objects to report their own l'
         b'ocation. However, in reporting continuously, objects consume conside'
         b'rable energy. To limit energy consumption: <a href="http://www.ipvs.'
         b'uni-stuttgart.de/abteilungen/vs/abteilung/mitarbeiter/tobias.farrell'
         b'/en">Tobias Farrell</a> puts forward a novel protocol (<a href="http'
         b'://www.informatik.uni-stuttgart.de/cgi-bin/NCSTRL/NCSTRL_view.pl?pro'
         b'jekt=SFB-627&amp;id=INPROC-2007-34&amp;mod=1&amp;engl=1&amp;inst">we'
         b'b</a>);   and <a href="http://wwwir.vub.ac.be/elec/NDEBLAUWE.htm">Ni'
         b'co Debauwe</a> and <a href="http://www.mobile.ifi.lmu.de/Members/">P'
         b'eter Ruppel </a>propose to combine GPS and GSM cell-ID positioning. '
         b' Maximilian Michel of <a href="http://www.docomoeurolabs.de/">DoCoMo'
         b'</a> looks at object tracking from a different angle: how to make it'
         b' scalable; and he does so by handling tracking data in a hierarchica'
         b'l p2p architecture. Another problem of tracking objects is how to  i'
         b'ndex their locations. And this is exactly the problem  <a href="http'
         b'://www.cl.cam.ac.uk/research/dtg/~rkh23/">Robert K. Harle</a> has ta'
         b'ckled  by adapting and combining two existing methods for indexing i'
         b'ndoor locations.</p>\n<p><strong>Mobile services</strong><br />\nF'
         b'irst there was simply &#8220;sensors&#8221;, now the  buzzwords in  '
         b'research circles of mobile services seem to be &#8220;<em>participat'
         b'ory sensing</em>&#8220;. <a href="http://www.dirk-trossen.de/">Dirk '
         b'Trossen</a> and Dana Pavel rightly say what they mean by those words'
         b' and list cases in which mobile phones may act as sensors to enable '
         b'participatory applications (eg, community-based environmental monito'
         b'ring, vehicle warning). They also propose a pub-sub architecture for'
         b' participatory sensing.</p>\n<p>The problem of how to deploy and '
         b'discover services in ubicomp  has won a significant following among '
         b'the papers presented. For example, to <em>discover</em> services, We'
         b'i Gao of <a href="http://www.asu.edu/">ASU</a> proposes the use of a'
         b' &#8220;hierarchical DHT&#8221;: ubicomp devices group into a set of'
         b' local DHTs whose clusterheads are connected to form a backbone; eac'
         b'h DHT then indexes the services that its ubicomp nodes offer (it wou'
         b'ld be very interesting to know the extent to which such an architect'
         b'ure is robust to device mobility). On the other hand, <a href="http:'
         b'//www.dbis.informatik.hu-berlin.de/mitarbeiter/derzeitige/artin-avan'
         b'es.html">Artin Avanes</a> proposes  different data retrieval strateg'
         b'ies (retrieval of device profiles) for a flexible <em>service deploy'
         b'ment</em> (a deployment that scales for different network topologies'
         b').</p>\n<p>Another promising research area is <em>body sensors</e'
         b'm>: &#8220;Mr Cowen&#8217;s model for running better meetings is har'
         b'd to beat: put in place a system (he suggests body sensors) that ena'
         b'bles participants to signal their boredom anonymously. When everyone'
         b' is known to be bored, the meeting halts.&#8221;(<a href="http://www'
         b'.economist.com/displaystory.cfm?story_id=9762740">link</a>) <img src'
         b'="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/wp-includes/images/smilies/icon_smile.'
         b'gif" alt=":-)" class="wp-smiley" />  In addition to this application'
         b' of body sensors, there are many others, and getting most of those a'
         b'pplications to work requires  adaptation to changes in context or in'
         b' service availability. <a href="http://www.doc.ic.ac.uk/~slk/Welcome'
         b'.html">Sye Loong Keoh</a> proposes a policy-based architecture for d'
         b'oing so.</p>\n<p><strong>Anonymity and Trust<br />\n</strong>In sh'
         b'aring digital content,  ubicomp devices bump into the problem of  ho'
         b'w actually to select  content (especially if content varies in quali'
         b'ty). Of course, devices should preferentially select high-quality co'
         b'ntent. To do so, one idea (to which some researchers are coming roun'
         b'd) is for ubicomp devices to run trust models. A trust model is a pi'
         b'ece of software that keeps track of who provides quality content and'
         b' who does not. <a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/">I<'
         b'/a> put forward a way with which mobile devices learn from their pas'
         b't experiences to set initial trust values (TRULLO &#8211; <a href="h'
         b'ttp://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/d.quercia/publications/quercia07trullo.'
         b'pdf">pdf</a> and <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/09/06/tru'
         b'st-bootstrapping-trullo-mobiquitous/">post</a>). And <a href="http:/'
         b'/www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/L.McNamara/">Liam</a> proposes to select con'
         b'tent by accounting for both trustworthiness and co-location of conte'
         b'nt producers (<a href="http://www.cs.ucl.ac.uk/staff/L.McNamara/mobi'
         b'q.pdf">pdf</a> and <a href="http://mobblog.cs.ucl.ac.uk/2007/08/17/m'
         b'obile-music/">post</a>) &#8211; this makes a lot of sense since ubic'
         b'omp devices (content producers) are usually mobile.<br />\nFinall'
         b'y,  consider a base station collecting data from sensors.  For some '
         b'applications, it may be important that the base station does so anon'
         b'ymously (ie,  it collects pieces of data without being able to link '
         b'them to the originating sensors). To this end, <a href="http://cs.un'
         b'm.edu/~jhorey/research/publications.html">James Horey</a> suggestes '
         b'that sensors do not send what they sense but send what they don&#821'
         b'7;t sense &#8211; the complement of sensed data. From those compleme'
         b'nts, the base station guesses what has been sensed. James showes how'
         b' this approach applies to traffic monitoring (<a href="http://cs.unm'
         b'.edu/~jhorey/research/mobiquitous07_negsurvey.pdf">pdf</a>).</p>'
